And look what happened...I came across True!  I started the first day and got interrupted half way through...but I came back to it later that day, started from the beginning and finished the whole thing. While the ending music was finishing, I was in tears, sobbing...I found my coach, my tribe, my life.  I love the Zen parts, I love Benji keeping you humble and not caring you are a big shot yoga star, and I love being given the permission to find what feels good to me.  After these 30 days (I finished day 3 today) I will join RISE and be a total 'Yoga with Adriene' groupy.  I have to take a 2 week break when I have a lumpectomy on my left breast May 2. Thankfully I'm able to ride a bicycle during those 2 weeks, but I will definitely miss my yoga with Adriene routine the most.  But I know it will be waiting for me to start back up.  How can something free be so priceless?  You are a blessing to me Adriene.  If you are ever in Kalamazoo, Michigan...you have a place to stay and you can put your yoga mat next to mine.

You are amazing Adriene and yoga is amazing. I have been doing Yoga with your videos for a year now and i really feel different. I used to have back and neck pain all the time, at some times it was so bad I couldn't wait to go to physiotherapy again when I had just left there. I also had no core/arm/leg strength at all, my stamina was the worst and I felt fat. I was basically really feeling really bad about my body. But then i commited, and started on your videos, then 30 day yoga camp. And other videos almost every day, for my back, my core, for when my emotional state was off, or when I just felt like being productive. Sometimes even twice a day!
Over the summer I started 30 days of Yoga (also partly in my holiday in France, that was amazing) and my back pain was sort of gone then.

I sort of stopped my commitment after that sadly, but picked it up quickly when my back became worse again and started Yoga Revolution. I was so proud when I managed to keep a full crow up for about 10 seconds orso! I just finished that over the new year and am now committed to TRUE (only two days behind on it). My neck and back still hurt, but significantly less. On top of that, I managed to do a (sort of) hand/shoulderstand on someone else in my Jiu-jitsu lesson today. Something which I've always failed miserably, because I didn't have the core strength. 
I still feel bad from time to time, but I have accepted that that is okay and I just have to stay myself and stay TRUE.

Anyway Sorry for the long post. I just want to say THANK YOU Adriene, THANK YOU! Thank you for all the advice and love, laughs and angry, crying and Benji, for having my back and most off all for all your effort in these videos. You've really helped me a lot.

You don't know how many lives you touch. I am a very driven person who has come under an overwhelming amount of stress and anxiety that has now taken its toll on my body. I was alway on the go, always wanting to be perfect- the perfect mom, the perfect employee, the perfect spouse... this drained me until one day when i was at work and had a full blown panic attack. I thought I was always a little anxious in the past and thought I understood what an anxiety attack felt like but nope...there I was short of breath feeling like i was going to pass out and was positive something was horribly wrong with me.. Well, now 4 months later I can tell you that I have put myself through too much, for too long. I was like a car running on empty and now every day have to work twice as hard to get back to feeling like myself. I was terrified to do anything including workout but one day I was home and told myself snap out of it. I went on youtube and typed "yoga for anxiety" and came across our videos. You helped pull me out of my shell. Some days are harder than others, but I know I want my life back. I must admit you have helped me more than you could imagine. In Hindu culture, the essence of all our emotions are the 9 Rasa. I have experienced each Rasa while doing Yoga With Adriene! Thank you Adriene for everything! The 9 Rasas are:

1. Love/Sringara‚Ä¶ It is the ultimate Rasa. The king or queen emotion that heals anything. It frees the ego and connects us to devotion. When you appreciate beauty it connects you to the source of love. It is the creative play between Shiva and Shakti, sun and moon, yin and yang. The purpose of the universe it to experience this divine love. This love exists in everything. It is within each one of us and radiates out to the cosmos.

2. Joy/Hasya‚Ä¶ This Rasa connects you to your humor, laughter, happiness and contentment. It is the extension of what you feel within love.

3. Wonder/Adhuta‚Ä¶ Curiosity, Mystery, Awe. When you become fascinated with the idea of life. It is your playfulness and innocence. You enter into complete appreciation and become an explorer or adventurer. It is magic!

4. Courage/Vira‚Ä¶ Bravery, Confidence, Pride. When you call upon your the Warrior that lives inside you. It is strong and vibrant.

5. Peace/Shanta‚Ä¶ Deep calmness and relaxation. When you become still and quiet. In peace you become so full that you are empty. You will not find peace anywhere but within.

6. Sadness/Karuna‚Ä¶ When you can experience sadness and connect it back to the cosmos, you then experience compassion. Compassion is what connects us all. Through compassion we can relate deeply to each other. When ones sadness is truly experienced around a situation it can give a sense of completion. Grieving is a key aspect in healing.

7. Anger/Raudra‚Ä¶ In anger we go into the fire. One moment of anger can destroy lifetimes of good merit. Respect anger. When anger isn‚Äôt honored it can bring up irritation, violence, hatred. Feel the anger. Let it move through you. Breath into the fire.

8. Fear/Bhayanaka‚Ä¶ Doubt, Worry, Insecurity. When we live our lives in fear, we shut down completely.

9. Disgust/Vibhasta‚Ä¶ self pity, Loathing, self hatred. Only through a loving emotion can you heal and appease disgust.

My personal yoga journey actually began at the same time as Adriene's first 30 day yoga challenge, and has ebbed and flowed under her guidance and my own personal exploration ever since.

Since then, I've learned a lot about presence, living with intention, and the power of what we can uncover on the mat to enrich life off the mat.

This year, I'm looking forward to practicing contentedness. As a goal oriented person, I often miss out on the beauty of the present moment, because my mind is ahead of me on what I can accomplish or achieve next. This often leaves me feeling dissatisfied, when I actually have so very much to be grateful for. So much achievement to already celebrate. 

I'm also committing to looking for opportunities to be grateful. And to generally be more fluid.
